More than 400 KCPE candidates in Kisumu Central constituency have received examination materials from Gilani Foundation in collaboration with James Were Foundation. The candidates from five schools within the informal settlement received clear geometrical sets, transparent clipboards and pencils. The schools include Pand Pieri, Dunga, Nanga, Ringroad and Bridge International primary schools. Speaking while distributing the materials, James Were said most of the students are needy and their parents cannot afford the exam materials. Were said the distribution of the materials has eased the burden to most parents. “We want the candidates to sit their exams with a peaceful mind so that they can fully concentrate,” he said. The former MCA told the students that those who will achieve 400 and above marks in their exams will get a full scholarship. “Since we started this program around 2013, each year, we give a scholarship to the best students from the schools who score 400 and above marks and we will continue to do this, “he said. Click here for the latest political news    